MSP_year <- MSP_data |>
  dplyr::mutate(YEAR = lubridate::year(.data$DATE)) |>
  dplyr::group_by(.data$YEAR) |>
  dplyr::summarize(
    PRCP = mean(.data$PRCP, na.rm = TRUE),
    TMAX = mean(.data$TMAX, na.rm = TRUE),
    TMIN = mean(.data$TMIN, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop") |>
  dplyr::ungroup()

ggplot2::ggplot(MSP_year) +
  ggplot2::aes(.data$YEAR, .data$TMAX) +
  ggplot2::geom_line() +
  ggplot2::ggtitle('Annual Max Temperature over Time for St Paul, MN') +
  ggplot2::xlab('Date') +
  ggplot2::ylab('Temperature (C)')

ggplot2::ggplot(MSP_year) +
  ggplot2::aes(.data$YEAR, .data$TMAX) +
  ggplot2::geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  ggplot2::geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = "y~x", se = FALSE,
                       color = "red") +
  ggplot2::ggtitle('Annual Max Temperature over Time for St Paul, MN') +
  ggplot2::xlab('Date') +
  ggplot2::ylab('Temperature (C)')

ggplot2::ggplot(MSP_year) +
  ggplot2::aes(.data$YEAR, .data$TMAX) +
  ggplot2::geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  ggplot2::geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = "y~x", se = FALSE,
                       color = "red") +
  ggplot2::geom_smooth(method = "loess", formula = "y~x", se = FALSE,
                       color = "green") +
  ggplot2::ggtitle('Annual Max Temperature over Time for St Paul, MN') +
  ggplot2::xlab('Date') +
  ggplot2::ylab('Temperature (C)')

This shows OLS (red) and LOESS (green), the latter being a smooth curve (locally polynomial) that captures local features such as the upswing at either end. This deals with outliers by locally smoothing rather than removing them.
